## Why This Is Asked
This question tests the ability to orchestrate host-level TLS termination with per-tenant dynamic routing, zero-downtime reloads, and proper security boundaries using Podman, systemd, SELinux, and nftables. It evaluates practical skills across containerization, reverse proxy configuration, and kernel policy tooling.

## Key Concepts
- Podman containerization with bind mounts for certificates and mappings
- SNI-based routing with per-tenant map files
- Live configuration reloads via nginx signal handling or systemd ExecReload
- Minimal SELinux policy to permit TLS termination and certificate reading
- nftables inbound rules for port 8443 and outbound rules for backend communication

## Code Example
```javascript
// Minimal watcher to rebuild nginx.conf from /srv/mappings
const fs = require('fs');
const { execSync } = require('child_process');

const mappingsPath = '/srv/mappings';
const template = 
`events { worker_connections 1024; }
http {
  map $ssl_server_name $backend {
    include /srv/mappings/*.map;
  }
  server {
    listen 8443 ssl;
    ssl_certificate /srv/certs/$ssl_server_name.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /srv/certs/$ssl_server_name.key;
    location / {
      proxy_pass http://$backend;
    }
  }
}`;

function reloadNginx() {
  fs.writeFileSync('/etc/nginx/nginx.conf', template);
  execSync('nginx -s reload', { stdio: 'inherit' });
}

fs.watch(mappingsPath, (eventType, filename) => {
  if (filename && filename.endsWith('.map')) {
    console.log(`Mapping changed: ${filename}`);
    reloadNginx();
  }
});
```

