## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design a containerized TLS gateway with per-tenant isolation and real-time traffic policing, plus zero-downtime upgrades and firewall hardening. It also probes integration of Podman, Nginx, SNI routing, mTLS to backends, and practical rollback plans.

## Key Concepts
- Podman and Nginx TLS termination with SNI routing
- mTLS backends and backend certificate verification
- Per-tenant rate limiting (limit_req_zone or Lua scripting)
- Dynamic config reloads via systemd drop-in for zero-downtime upgrades
- nftables rules for inbound 8443 and outbound to backends
- Concrete test plans for bursts and rollback

## Code Example
```nginx
# nginx.conf (excerpt)
http {
  limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=tenantA:10m rate=10r/s;
  limit_req_zone $binary_remote_addr zone=tenantB:10m rate=5r/s;
  server {
    listen 8443 ssl;
    server_name tenantA.example;
    ssl_certificate /path/a.crt;
    ssl_certificate_key /path/a.key;
    location / {
      limit_req zone=tenantA burst=100 nodelay;
      proxy_pass https://10.0.2.50:8080;
      proxy_ssl_server_name on;
      proxy_ssl_verify on;
    }
  }
  server {
    listen 8443 ssl;
    server_name tenantB.example;
    location / {
      limit_req zone=tenantB burst=50;
      proxy_pass https://10.0.2.51:8080;
      proxy_ssl_server_name on;
      proxy_ssl_verify on;
    }
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you scale tenants beyond two while preserving fairness? 
- What changes for a third backend or different TLS ciphers? 
- How would you monitor and alert on rate-limit breaches and reload status?

