## Why This Is Asked

Evaluate ability to implement host integrity controls with minimal downtime using native RH tooling, idempotence, and rollback.

## Key Concepts

- rpm -V usage for binary integrity
- systemd service and timer
- Baseline diffing and logging
- Alerting and rollback strategy
- Reinstall path from diffs

## Code Example

```javascript
const { execSync } = require('child_process');
const fs = require('fs');
const baseline = '/var/log/integrity/baseline.txt';
const current = execSync('rpm -V -a').toString();
const base = fs.readFileSync(baseline, 'utf8');
const nl = String.fromCharCode(10);
const diff = current.split(/\\r?\\n/).filter(l => !base.includes(l)).join(nl);
if (diff) {
  fs.appendFileSync('/var/log/sys_integrity.log', diff + nl);
  console.log('ALERT');
} else {
  console.log('OK');
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you adapt this for multi-host environments and centralize reporting?
- How would you minimize false positives around legitimate upgrades?

